The lowest status, because it is regarded as begging, was assigned to the children with babies on their hips (Fig. 3
                        ) who approach tourists and plead for “milk for my baby”. These children are referred to colloquially as the “milk scam kids” and ask tourists to buy powdered milk for their babies from a complicit store. The child then hands the donated milk to a managing ‘overlord’ who sells the milk back to the shop at a reduced price. This practice has been identified and challenged as a scam by the Childsafe Network NGO (Fig. 4
                        ). Local Cambodians call these children kheng somtean, or “beg milk from tourists and sell back for money”. Appealing to the emotions of female tourists was a successful strategy as explained by Sandra (late 50s); “I couldn't resist buying milk for the babies despite the warnings (see Fig. 4). I am a mother!” The power of the group involved in the scam is expressed in their monopolisation of a particular location, achieved by alleged payments to police by the overlord. Social workers from Angkor Hospital for Children confirmed the milk scam children do not attend school. The social workers had tried on many occasions and in multiple ways to connect with the group to ascertain their level of well-being and provide free bottled milk for the babies. These offers were rejected and hospital management determined that attempts to connect must be discontinued in the short term after threats of violence. For this reason, the social workers advised against my attempts to connect with the milk scam kids.

Asserting a right to sell and thereby fund their education, the successful street-sellers demonstrated strategies to increase the likelihood of a sale. The most successful sellers immediately refuted the NGO marketing message that child street-sellers do not go to school by promoting their status as students and showcasing proof of their attendance;
                           I love school and want to be a teacher. I carry my school report with me all the time when selling and show it to the tourists. When tourists see my report they talk to me and ask questions about my school. These tourists will often buy a book.
                           (Srey Pan, girl 12)

Kim (young woman 23) also from Sokhem had worked as a seller outside Angkor Wat since she was eight. Kim had learned excellent English by conversing with tourists, who had often given her extra money to finance her schooling;
                           When I was young, Western tourists often gave me extra money for schooling, once as much as USD300 in a day. The money was good back then and many children were able to stay at school because they could pay for their schooling.
                           (Kim, girl 23)

Those that remained selling on the street expressed dissatisfaction toward Government and police regulations they believed created major and deliberate obstacles to improve their circumstances;
                           The Government does not care about us, they only care about themselves. Selling to tourists is a tradition in our village and it is why so many children could go to school. Now because of the police it is difficult to sell and now many children cannot go to school. It also means often there is no money for food.
                           (Proen, boy 15)

Most families grow rice although the number of children and inconsistent weather has resulted in insufficient food;
                           All my family help with the rice crop. This year there have been floods and so we will not have enough rice for the year, maybe only six or seven months. This is why selling is so important.
                           (Phirun, boy 13)
